<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1785,2028]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1436,151,250]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,2001,2027]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Most closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Miyamoto &amp; Lee" authorityYear="1966" box="[588,719,2001,2027]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Pilophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="okamotoi">
<emphasis box="[588,719,2001,2027]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">P. okamotoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from which this new species can be distinguished by characters in the above key (couplet 24) and different shape of the genitalia (e.g., hypophysis of right paramere reduced; endosomal median process with shorter branch more than half length of longer branch; apical ridge distinctly widened; and basal 2/3 of interramal lobe lacking spinules).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
