<subSubSection lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1436,1930,2029]" lastBlockId="24.[151,1437,151,897]" lastPageId="24" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1930,1956]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Description.</emphasis>
Body brown to chestnut brown, moderate in size, moderately constricted; dorsal surface only with uniformly distributed, simple, short, reclining setae. Head shiny fuscous; head with eyes a little wider than high; vertex relatively wide. Antenna dark brown; segment I pale brown;, basal 2/3 of segment II reddish brown; basal half of segment III and extreme base of IV creamy yellow; segment II weakly clavate, about as long as or shorter than maximum width of hemelytra. Labium shiny chestnut brown, rather short, slightly exceeding base of mesocoxa. Pronotum fuscous, rather weakly shining; scutellum dark castaneous, with silvery scale-like setae aggregated on each corner; pleura dark brown; mesepimeron uniformly covered with scale-like setae. Hemelytron matte, with rather sparsely distributed, simple, semierect setae; median band of silvery scale-like setae on corium shifted or interrupted at M-vein (media); posterolateral part of corium (posterior to median band of scale-like setae) and cuneus more or less darkened; membrane pale smoky brown. Coxae pale brown, except for darkened mesocoxa; legs brown; profemur and each tibia paler; tarsi pale brown; tarsomere III darkened; pretarsal structure as in 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 17. Scanning electron micrographs for Pilophorus okamotoi (with black circles●) and P. satoyamanus n. sp. A–B, I–J. Anterior body, left lateral view. C, K. Thoracic pleura, left lateral view. D, N, O. Apex of pygophore, left lateral view. E. Apex of pygophore, with parameres and exposed endosoma. F–G. Endosoma. H, L–M. Metatarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596075/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Fig. 
<specimenCount box="[151,207,439,465]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="generic">17M</specimenCount>
</figureCitation>
. Abdomen dark brown, with clustered scale-like setae laterally on sterna III–IV. Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1330,1432,439,465]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[173,1401,286,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-61@23.[164,1423,273,1765]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Male endosoma (vesica) and endosoma of Japanese Pilophorus spp. A. P. choii (from Otaru). B. P. erraticus (Nagasaki). C. P. pseudoperplexus (Kanagawa). D. P.okamotoi (Tsushima Is.). E. P.satoyamanus n. sp. (Kochi).F. P.setulosellus n. sp. (Hiroshima). G. Same (Nara). H. P. setulosus (Sapporo, type locality, Salix). I. Same, (Shiretoko, Artemisia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596059/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,178,475,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1914,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1883]" captionTargetId="figure-18@31.[151,1436,181,1890]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 17. Scanning electron micrographs for Pilophorus okamotoi (with black circles●) and P. satoyamanus n. sp. A–B, I–J. Anterior body, left lateral view. C, K. Thoracic pleura, left lateral view. D, N, O. Apex of pygophore, left lateral view. E. Apex of pygophore, with parameres and exposed endosoma. F–G. Endosoma. H, L–M. Metatarsus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596075/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">17</figureCitation>
N–O): Parameres heavily setose (17N–O); left paramere with sensory lobe strongly projected left-laterally; right paramere ovoid, with tiny hypophysis; endosoma with bifurcate median process and distinctly widened apical ridge (
<figureCitation box="[160,258,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1788,1812]" captionTargetBox="[173,1401,286,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-61@23.[164,1423,273,1765]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. Male endosoma (vesica) and endosoma of Japanese Pilophorus spp. A. P. choii (from Otaru). B. P. erraticus (Nagasaki). C. P. pseudoperplexus (Kanagawa). D. P.okamotoi (Tsushima Is.). E. P.satoyamanus n. sp. (Kochi).F. P.setulosellus n. sp. (Hiroshima). G. Same (Nara). H. P. setulosus (Sapporo, type locality, Salix). I. Same, (Shiretoko, Artemisia)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596059/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 11E</figureCitation>
); shorter branch of median process more than half length of longer branch. Female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1295,1378,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[167,1419,463,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-137@25.[164,1423,453,1836]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Female bursa copulatrix and eggs (B, E, H) of Japanese Pilophorus spp. A, C, F, K–L. Dorsal view. D, G, I, J, M. Ventral view, with vestibular sclerite (VES). A–B. P. erraticus (Nagasaki). C–E. P. pseudoperplexus (Otaru). F–H. P. satoyamanus n. sp. (Ibaraki). I. P. okamotoi (Tsushima Is.). J–K. P. setulosellus n. sp. (Hiroshima). L–M. P. setulosus (Asahikawa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596061/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Figs 12</figureCitation>
F–H, 19D–F): Sclerotized ring thick-rimmed, narrowly folded laterally (
<figureCitation box="[898,998,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[167,1419,463,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-137@25.[164,1423,453,1836]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Female bursa copulatrix and eggs (B, E, H) of Japanese Pilophorus spp. A, C, F, K–L. Dorsal view. D, G, I, J, M. Ventral view, with vestibular sclerite (VES). A–B. P. erraticus (Nagasaki). C–E. P. pseudoperplexus (Otaru). F–H. P. satoyamanus n. sp. (Ibaraki). I. P. okamotoi (Tsushima Is.). J–K. P. setulosellus n. sp. (Hiroshima). L–M. P. setulosus (Asahikawa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596061/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 12F</figureCitation>
); vestibular sclerite rather narrow (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[167,1419,463,1828]" captionTargetId="figure-137@25.[164,1423,453,1836]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Female bursa copulatrix and eggs (B, E, H) of Japanese Pilophorus spp. A, C, F, K–L. Dorsal view. D, G, I, J, M. Ventral view, with vestibular sclerite (VES). A–B. P. erraticus (Nagasaki). C–E. P. pseudoperplexus (Otaru). F–H. P. satoyamanus n. sp. (Ibaraki). I. P. okamotoi (Tsushima Is.). J–K. P. setulosellus n. sp. (Hiroshima). L–M. P. setulosus (Asahikawa)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596061" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596061/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 12G</figureCitation>
); basal 2/3 of interramal lobe lacking spinules (
<figureCitation box="[735,839,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 19" captionStartId="33.[151,250,1908,1932]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1874]" captionTargetId="figure-18@33.[151,1436,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 19. Scanning electron micrographs of female genitalia for Pilophorus spp.. A–C. Pilophorus okamotoi. D–F. P. satoyamanus n. sp. G–I. P. pseudoperplexus. J–L. P. setulosellus n. sp. M–O. P. setulosus. A–B, D–E, G–H, J–K, M–N. Posterior wall of bursae. C, F. Ovipositor (gonapophysis II). I, L, O. Bursa copulatrix, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4596079" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4596079/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Fig. 19D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
